": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request,re,html\ns=urllib.request.urlopen(urllib.request.Request('https://netty.io/wiki/java-24-and-sun.misc.unsafe.html', headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'}), timeout=15).read().decode('utf-8','replace')\n# Print section Netty 4.2 and Unsafe around it as HTML-stripped\ntext=html.unescape(re.sub(r'<[^>]+>',' ',s)); text=re.sub(r'\\s+',' ',text)\nidx=text.find('Netty 4.2 and Unsafe')\nprint(text[idx:idx+2500])\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1995, "output": 1199, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 41594, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782658258795, "responseId": "resp_0c8f081531c55ef9016a4134d376548190b267958293f688af"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_XEWbbWVKHeJzGvdWznu0WOjP|fc_0c8f081531c55ef9016a4134e22148819086e916c051b0a94c", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Netty 4.2 and Unsafe Netty 4.2.0 and 4.2.1 take no special precautions, and produce warnings the same as Netty 4.1 (excluding 4.1.120 and 4.1.121) does. Netty 4.2.2 and newer adds support for using MemorySegment APIs to avoid relying on Unsafe . The memory segment support comes in two variants: Preferred: Linking directly to the system malloc and free functions. ( PR #15366 ) This mechanism is supported from Java 24 onwards, but it requires native access to be enabled. To enable native access, the JVM must be launched with this command line argument: --enable-native-access=io.netty.common This mechanism is available since Netty 4.2.3. This mechanism is the preferred way, because it has the least amount of overhead when allocating and deallocating. Fallback: Using shared memory segment arenas. ( PR #15231 ) This mechanism does not require native access. However, due to JDK bugs, it can only be used from Java 25 onwards ( PR #15338 ) This mechanism is available since Netty 4.2.2. This mechanism is the last resort fall-back because it does not require native access. However, releasing shared arenas is expensive because it involves thread-local handshakes (a cheaper form of safepoint) and JIT de-optimization. What Netty uses Unsafe for Netty and its native transports need native (off-heap) memory to move data faster to and from the operating system, i.e. without copying data into and out of the heap as well. To effectively work with native memory, Netty needs a way to not only allocate memory, but also deallocate it as soon as it's done using it. Netty needs Unsafe to access the cleaner instance inside the direct ByteBuffers . The cleaner is the mechanism used to deallocate the memory in direct ByteBuffer instances. When Unsafe is not available to Netty, then the ByteBuffer cleaner is also not available to Netty, and it instead has to rely on the garbage collector for releasing the memory. The garbage collector runs in response to heap memory pressure, but direct buffers do not produce much memory pressure on the heap. This causes native memory to be released after a greater delay than strictly necessary, which in turn increases memory usage. The JDK attempts to work around this by occasionally running the garbage collector explicitly when allocating new direct ByteBuffer instances, and then sleeping for 100 milliseconeds. This behavior, the increased explicit GC and the 100 milliseconds sleep, is unacceptable to Netty. We cannot accept sleeping or any other b\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782658275216}]}
